04396nam a22005655i 9780774864435DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748644357 a10.59962/97807748644352doi  a(DE-B1597)661497  a(OCoLC)1182633412  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE78.C2bH37 2020 7aHIS0520002bisacsh04a305.897/0712231 aHarris, Cole, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Bounded Land :bReflections on Settler Colonialism in Canada /cCole Harris. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b22 maps, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tEarly Encounters -- tThe Fraser Canyon Encountered -- tImagining and Claiming the Land -- tVoices of Smallpox around the Strait of Georgia -- tEarly Settlements -- tAcadia: Settling the Marshlands -- tOf Poverty and Helplessness in Petite-Nation -- tThe Settlement of Mono Township -- tThe Architecture of Settlement -- tEuropean Beginnings in the Northwest Atlantic -- tThe Overseas Simplification of Europe -- tCreating Place in Early Canada -- tReconfiguring British Columbia -- tThe Making of the Lower Mainland -- tThe Struggle with Distance -- tIndigenous Space -- tTheorizing Settler Colonialism -- tMaking an Immigrant Society -- tHow Did Colonialism Dispossess? -- tPostscript: The Boundaries of Settler Colonialism -- tNotes and Further Readings -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCanada is a country of bounded spaces – a nation situated between rock and cold to the north and a political border to the south. In A Bounded Land, Cole Harris seeks answers to a sweeping question: How was society reorganized – for Indigenous and non-Indigenous people alike – when Europeans resettled this distinctive land? Through a series of vignettes that focus on people’s experiences on the ground, Harris exposes the underlying architecture of settler colonialism as it grew and evolved, from the first glimpses of new lands and peoples, to the immigrant experience in early Canada, to the dispossession and resettlement of First Nations in British Columbia. By considering the whole territory that became Canada over 500 years and focusing on sites of colonial domination rather than settler texts, Harris unearths fresh insights on the continuing and growing influence of Indigenous peoples and argues that Canada’s boundedness is ultimately drawing the country toward its Indigenous roots.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous peoplesxColonizationzCanadaxHistory. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxGovernment relationsxHistory. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Historical Geography.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311141765340uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486443540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774864435423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774864435/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-141765-3  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles